snippet.textDisplay:
Re: Johnny Depp and Amber Heard
Edit:
I'm not looking to debate or offer my opinion, but as someone who is an expert in this topic, I wanted to share some information so that people could be better informed on a topic that isn't regularly discussed.


I encourage people to learn about resistive and reactive violence. A victim may fight back or sometimes even preemptively use physical violence when they see that an abusive partner is escalating to physical violence again. It's likely that there were some domestic violence experts involved in the legal process of this case and they would know better than anyone who is the victim and who is the perpetrator of the abuse. Everyone else can only really guess.

I wanted to also include the definition of domestic violence that a lot of experts in this field use. We define domestic violence as an intentional pattern of behavior one uses to gain and maintain power and control over someone with whom they are in a relationship or were previously in a relationship with.

12:05 The media likes to portray Andrew Yang as someone who is the least likely to win. I say, I really don't care if someone is not going to win. Voting should be based on who you want as President. Otherwise you're just a cog in the machine of propaganda. You're not thinking for yourself, and we're no longer a democracy. We're just idiots brainwashed to believe in voting for whoever is the most corrupt and affluent, who will always win, and continue to maintain the status quo (e.g. poverty and homelessness).

In order to see real change in the country we have to vote for the person the media (or rather those who control the media), don't want.

Now, consider what has happened to Andrew Yang. His mic was shut off during one of the debates. Then, he was given the least amount of time to speak by far, and called on last. Early polling in December was denied so he was not allowed to attend the last debate. In a graphic of presidential candidates, they replaced his face with another Chinese person. In every single interview, the interviewer always asks (or is required to), "WHAT IF YOU DON'T WIN??"

All of this designed from the beginning to reinforce the fact that he's irrelevant, he doesn't matter. Only the popular people matter. But people need to learn, popular ≠ "the best."

snippet.textDisplay: As a women who has been emotionally and physically abused from a very young age, I will always support others, especially women, when they do decide to come forth. People do need to talk about abuse in general and how it does have an effect. But... here's my thing, when Amber Heard started to come out about the accusations of Johnny Depp something in my gut was telling me that all of her accusations are either a lie or very exaggerated. I've been a huge Johnny Depp fan, but I was also a big fan for Amber Heard. To me she was a rising actress to keep an eye on and I was so happy when they got together because she seemed wonderful and just nice. But as a kid to both manipulating parents, one a physical abuser and one a narcissistic who emotionally abused, I knew something seem off. It was very sad to see because no one believed Johnny Depp's side to things because he's the guy so he's automatically the aggressor, but I truly always thought she might have been the true aggressor and that audio provides that. Coming from personal experience I think Amber Heard is a narcissist and she's just really good at hiding it. A lot of people think I'm rude for disregarding or having as little respect for my mom because they only think of their own mom and in meeting my mom you wouldn't even suspect the things she's done to me, because narcissistic people are very good at hiding their bad side. That's all they know and in their mind they will do anything in their power to make everyone else seem like the bad guy. But when people do actually meet that side of my mom they finally understand and apologize for assuming any different. And I'm not saying I should assume differently with this situation as well, but when you do come from a family of abuse you can usually tell when people are straight with you and who's crying wolf. Abuse feels like a nightmare that you can't wake up from, you feel even ashamed of it at times. I've never felt that genuine emotion that comes with the abuse she claimed, so I could never had that connection to her accusations, and that voice recording proves why. I think Amber Heard is a genuinely sick person for using the word "abusive" to cover her own abuse, to try to destroy someone emotionally, physically, and career wise. And yes, I'm assuming all this, but it's from the best educated guess I could give. And for her to claim this makes everyone else's abuse story feel invalidated and like they are not going to be heard because she decided that's what it means to be "abused." As a public figure, she can have that power and it's very messed up and immature that that's how she decided to use her power for her own personal gain, to bully others, and destroy.
